# Swift / SwiftUI conventions

## Style and clarity

- Prefer `struct` for models and value types; use `class` only when reference identity or Objective-C interop requires it.
- Mark UI entry types with `@MainActor` when they touch UIKit/SwiftUI app lifecycle (match `AppEnvironment`).
- Use `async throws` for network and persistence boundaries; propagate typed errors (`APIError`, domain errors) instead of empty `catch` blocks.
- Keep functions small and named for behavior (verbs for methods, nouns for properties). Avoid boolean trap parameters; use labeled arguments or small enums when clarity suffers.

## SwiftUI

- Extract subviews when a `body` grows unwieldy; keep environment reads (`injected`, bindings) at the top level of the view that needs them.
- Prefer `@Observable` / observation only if the project already adopts it in that area; otherwise stay consistent with `Store` + `Combine` patterns already in use.

## Access control

- Tighten access (`private`, `fileprivate`) for helpers; keep protocols and DI-facing types `internal` unless a module boundary exists.

## Apple APIs

- Use Swift API Design Guidelines naming. Prefer standard library and SwiftUI patterns over custom wrappers unless they add clear value in this codebase.
